snippet.textDisplay: I personally liked the film, it was fun all the way for me. Yeah, the Emperor was kinda forced in. But to be fair, the acting was great. The story was kind of a mess, but it provided a fulfilling end to the saga. I personally liked the ending. Yeah, it tried to have its Endgame ending, but the fight between Rey and Kylo Ren was very entertaining. I went to this movie as a fan of movies first and then as a fan of Star Wars. It has flaws and it could be argued the last two films was better, but it was my favorite of the sequel trilogy. It is sort of a guilty pleasure, but for what it is, I can say I enjoyed the Rise of Skywalker.

snippet.textDisplay:
After watching it the first time I though: ok I didn't like it but maybe I need to watch it again since there was a lot thrown at us in just one movie, so maybe I missed something, maybe after watching it again I might like it more.
But after I had time to really digest what I had seen, I came to the conclusion that no amount of re-watching will make me like the movie. As a matter of fact I can't, just the thought of it makes me mad and sad at the same time. Mad at Disney for clearly not having a fucking clue of what they were doing to this new trilogy, and sad because I will never be able to see Star Wars in the same light as I did before. Honestly Disney needs to tread carefully, they are very close to completely ruining Star Wars, the only thing right now keeping it from happening is The Mandalorian and how good the first season was, but I really think that there is no room for another bad movie/series.
Edit: The comment section of any youtube video is garbage. Instead of people having a honest discussion, we get pretty much a copy&past meme going on.

snippet.textDisplay: Hi there. I don't wish to criticise this video so much as to say I found it just made me rather sad. I hugely appreciated and valued your older videos in their defense and appreciation of 'Awakens' and 'Jedi', (while critiquing them in reasonable ways) in fact they probably were (and still are) very, very significant in resisting a huge amount of wilfully thoughtless nonsense argued about them, as you yourself found! So while I respect your opinion of the sequels as it now stands, (and I agree with many of your specific criticisms of 'Rise', which is a very disappointing film) I can't help but feel bad that your position seems to have soured so much, to the extent of pretty much dismissing the sequels entirely. And to go beyond opinion, I recall quite a few specific virtues of 'Awakens' and 'Jedi' you discussed previously that directly contradict the idea that they are simply "a worse remake of the originals", such as your praising the new arc for Luke in 'Jedi' and the pointlessness of repeating his old one. (If I were to debate this myself, I might go on to find a huge amount that is different in terms of characterisation-- to the extent that I'm not sure how much such a statement has been thought through for this video. Pardon me if that's rude, but it just does baffle me that much.) I do still respect past work of yours tremendously-- and as I say, I do agree with most of this video, barring the general statements about the sequels being retreads and their characters being lesser copies, especially Rey (unless Luke, too, was essentially Cinderella in a Mad Max film. Don't recall that part of his introduction, somehow.) Anyway, I hope your view of these movies becomes more positive in time, if you ever go back to them. Have a very Happy New Year.

snippet.textDisplay:
So it turns out Rey being Palpatine's granddaughter actually was planned from the beginning -- her theme music shares a leitmotif with Palpatine's from the Prequel Trilogy, and in her lightsaber duel with Kylo, she uses some of the exact same choreography as Palpatine when he fought Windu. Which, aside from being an admittedly genius subtle hint, also helps explain how she was able to hold her own with a lightsaber in the first place. What made Palpatine so dangerous in lightsaber duels was his uncanny ability to basically copy his opponent's fighting style on the fly, (sort of like Taskmaster from Marvel). That sort of thing would involve muscle memory rather than just "because the Force", so it could easily be hereditary, (which makes even more sense, since it'd have skipped a generation with Rey).


I still feel like her being amazing at using the Force because of bloodline is lame, though. Anakin had absurd potential from birth, too, but he still needed actual training. I think it would have been pretty neat if Rey's relation to Palpatine resulted in her just being inexplicably good with a lightsaber, rather than that AND being good at using the Force. Something in a similar vein to the Legend of Korra, where she's amazing at one thing but really struggles with something else -- in this instance, Force powers associated with the Light Side. Would've made her a lot less Mary Sue, and also would have made her training with Luke way more interesting and involved. Like, imagine her being able to nearly match Luke in a lightsaber duel to his surprise, but sucking really bad at learning to use Jedi Force techniques, resulting in her getting frustrated and accidentally letting loose some Dark Side powers and THEN Luke refuses to train her.

snippet.textDisplay: I really appreciate you going back on the fact that you just made your Last Jedi review as a response to the hatred and less so a response to the film, its impressive to see a opinion actually grow on Youtube. That being said calling it a myopic view of the franchise is simply a criticism taken out of context, which you yourself always talk against. The film has aged poorly due to the response of Rise of Skywalker; going back now I still feel that sense of childhood wonderment that made me love the original films whenever I see the ending, and despite the obvious flaws associated with the writing and faulty pacing the movie still does so much right in terms of building the universe that its easy to look past. The film was an obvious flash in the pan in the overall universe and unfortunately is now regarded as "that star wars movie" more so due to its place in between the two Abrams directed films. Return of the Jedi experienced several of the same flaws as Rise, mostly due to the rushed nature of the conclusion to a story that could never fit within a three movie format, and as such I imagine thirty years from now The Last Jedi is going to be viewed through the same lens as Empire; the odd ball movie of the trilogy that tried to paint a better overall picture of what the universe could look like outside of the mindless plot that pushed the story along as a whole. The characters grew and the plot was allowed to sit back a bit in order to grow suspense and make us actually care about whats going on outside of the singular movie that was the original Star Wars. Sorry to comment on a completely separate movie on this video, but I feel that this movie should only heighten the overall opinion of The Last Jedi rather than tear down the entirety of the Disney Star Wars films as a whole. Hope you read this comment I'd really be interested to hear your take.

snippet.textDisplay: I feel like this is one of those movies that is akin to Mission Impossible where, objectively speaking, it has extreme flaws that discredit it from being great cinema and instead is created with the sole intent of providing a simple but thrilling experience (along with money of course), bringing it to the realm of subjectivity, left to be decided by audiences. Many people who aren't necessarily die-hard fans but grew up with the series enjoy it because it provides a satisfying end to one of the biggest influencers in pop culture, or perhaps the battles are very thrilling. I have really no problem with this as I greatly enjoyed the film, I can't say it is anything great objectively, but I definitely had more fun than when I normally watch a movie. The problem with this subjectivity is that if a person doesn't get the intended result, which is fair and possible as that's what subjectivity is, the film is ultimately left with no value, which is unfortunate. My main point here is that this is a film, nay a series, with purely subjective value, as it holds very little objective value, and is created with the intent to entertain, not impress. It falls to us to decide if we're okay with there being movies made in this way, I personally am as there will always be films seeking to impress and be better, but sometimes it's nice to have a simple, fun film. But that's just me, I'm only one person, and I don't represent the entire media-consuming audience, no one does except the audience itself.
